1
00:00:00,785 --> 00:00:03,138
Mrs. Owen is expecting
a lot of guests.

2
00:00:03,256 --> 00:00:04,303
She chose you.

3
00:00:04,562 --> 00:00:06,188
Welcome to Soldier Island.

4
00:00:06,902 --> 00:00:08,933
Mr. Lombard, you seem
to be under the impression

5
00:00:09,051 --> 00:00:10,885
that I am a particular kind
of woman.

6
00:00:11,097 --> 00:00:12,965
And I assure you that I'm not.

7
00:00:12,978 --> 00:00:14,525
They're the 10 little soldiers...

8
00:00:14,649 --> 00:00:15,875
You know, from the poem.

9
00:00:16,297 --> 00:00:17,779
Ladies and gentlemen...

10
00:00:17,829 --> 00:00:18,779
Who is that?

11
00:00:18,846 --> 00:00:21,128
You are charged
with the following indictments.

12
00:00:21,493 --> 00:00:24,531
Philip Lombard...
That you did murder 21 men.

13
00:00:24,771 --> 00:00:26,781
What the hell
are they playing at?!

14
00:00:26,944 --> 00:00:28,570
Malicious nonsense.

15
00:00:28,676 --> 00:00:30,874
Cyril.
I really tried to save him.

16
00:00:31,442 --> 00:00:32,462
I almost drowned.

17
00:00:32,754 --> 00:00:33,721
Twenty-one men?

18
00:00:34,320 --> 00:00:37,252
I'm the only one telling the
truth in a room full of liars.

19
00:00:37,651 --> 00:00:38,664
Who is it?

20
00:00:39,942 --> 00:00:41,069
We are cut off.

21
00:00:42,462 --> 00:00:43,748
Rats in a barrel.

22
00:00:44,527 --> 00:00:45,601
Almonds.

23
00:00:45,750 --> 00:00:46,949
Almonds be buggered.

24
00:00:48,060 --> 00:00:49,073
Cyanide.

25
00:02:00,500 --> 00:02:01,948
None of you moved them?

26
00:02:02,999 --> 00:02:04,170
- No.
- No.

27
00:02:04,982 --> 00:02:06,116
Was it you, Doctor?

28
00:02:07,995 --> 00:02:09,004
No.

29
00:02:12,161 --> 00:02:13,623
How did Mrs. Rogers die?

30
00:02:15,571 --> 00:02:16,709
I have no idea.

31
00:02:16,921 --> 00:02:18,331
Did you give her something?

32
00:02:18,746 --> 00:02:20,431
Yes... a mild sedative.

33
00:02:20,550 --> 00:02:21,860
Did you give her too much?

34
00:02:21,986 --> 00:02:25,557
Miss Claythorne, I warned you
against becoming hysterical.

35
00:02:25,766 --> 00:02:27,076
It's the poem.

36
00:02:27,194 --> 00:02:28,904
It's the poem.
Don't you see?

37
00:02:29,415 --> 00:02:31,049
Ten little soldier boys.

38
00:02:31,160 --> 00:02:33,627
One choked himself,
one overslept himself,

39
00:02:33,739 --> 00:02:34,615
and then there were eight.

40
00:02:34,731 --> 00:02:36,364
There were 10 of these
and 10 of us,

41
00:02:36,476 --> 00:02:37,872
and now there's eight.

42
00:02:39,728 --> 00:02:42,390
Oh, General... General,
did you move the figures?

43
00:02:42,799 --> 00:02:43,795
What?

44
00:02:43,616 --> 00:02:45,326
The figures.
Did you move the figures?

45
00:02:45,440 --> 00:02:46,955
No.
Of course not.

46
00:02:47,066 --> 00:02:48,581
Perhaps
it was you, Miss Claythorne.

47
00:02:48,692 --> 00:02:50,684
- You discovered it.
- Of course it wasn't me.

48
00:02:50,795 --> 00:02:52,937
- Why would I do that?
- To be the center of attention.

49
00:02:53,055 --> 00:02:54,539
Do you crave attention,
Miss Claythorne?

50
00:02:54,643 --> 00:02:56,276
Any kind of attention?

51
00:02:56,388 --> 00:02:58,887
- What are you talking about?
- Shall we just have breakfast?

52
00:03:03,807 --> 00:03:07,053
It was dreadful news
about Mrs. Rogers.

53
00:03:07,453 --> 00:03:09,325
She was a wonderful cook.

54
00:03:09,637 --> 00:03:11,347
Such a shame.

55
00:03:13,085 --> 00:03:16,074
This egg is four minutes
precisely, is it?

56
00:03:18,429 --> 00:03:19,563
Yes, madam.

57
00:03:19,974 --> 00:03:23,545
Rogers, did you take away
two of these figures?

58
00:03:24,208 --> 00:03:25,203
No, miss.

59
00:03:25,602 --> 00:03:29,112
Condolences, Mr. Rogers.
When are you expecting Narracott?

60
00:03:29,018 --> 00:03:30,251
Mid-to late morning, sir.

61
00:03:30,366 --> 00:03:32,390
His timekeeping
is somewhat erratic.

62
00:03:34,328 --> 00:03:35,875
Will that be all?

63
00:03:35,994 --> 00:03:38,461
Yes. Thank you, Rogers.
Thank you very much.

64
00:03:40,317 --> 00:03:43,022
Tony Marston was young
and strong.

65
00:03:43,133 --> 00:03:45,157
He didn't die
from some stimulant.

66
00:03:46,069 --> 00:03:47,346
Perhaps he was poisoned.

67
00:03:47,457 --> 00:03:50,714
And... And Mrs. Rogers...
Perhaps she was given too much.

68
00:03:50,828 --> 00:03:53,490
What drugs do you have
in your medical bag, Doctor?

69
00:03:53,604 --> 00:03:55,166
Why did you even bring it?

70
00:03:55,985 --> 00:03:57,576
You are a guest.
It's not work.

71
00:03:57,690 --> 00:03:59,594
Actually, it is work.

72
00:03:59,712 --> 00:04:03,608
I was trying to maintain some
sort of professional discretion.

73
00:04:03,719 --> 00:04:08,447
However, Mrs. Owen suffers
from female neuroses.

74
00:04:08,558 --> 00:04:11,220
My speciality
is women's disorders.

75
00:04:12,049 --> 00:04:14,667
Mr. Owen engaged me
in a professional capacity

76
00:04:14,786 --> 00:04:16,214
to tend to his wife!

77
00:04:16,332 --> 00:04:17,803
Gave up on the surgery, then,
Doctor?

78
00:04:17,919 --> 00:04:20,982
No. People do not just die
out of nowhere for no reason.

79
00:04:21,092 --> 00:04:24,431
They die because something
was done to them by someone.

80
00:04:24,741 --> 00:04:25,855
I'm gonna check your bag.

81
00:04:25,970 --> 00:04:27,938
- Don't you dare touch...
- What have you got to hide?

82
00:04:28,033 --> 00:04:29,224
How about I do it?

83
00:04:30,930 --> 00:04:33,311
I'm not being searched
like some grubby criminal.

84
00:04:33,189 --> 00:04:35,851
Then what if the general
goes with him?

85
00:04:36,431 --> 00:04:37,779
He's an honorable man.

86
00:04:38,222 --> 00:04:39,217
Fine!

87
00:04:38,742 --> 00:04:39,575
But while you're at it,

88
00:04:39,694 --> 00:04:43,352
you might want to search
Judge Wargrave's case as well.

89
00:04:43,863 --> 00:04:45,373
I know where I've seen you before.

90
00:04:45,842 --> 00:04:48,385
Chap who has the clinic
beneath mine in Harley Street,

91
00:04:48,977 --> 00:04:50,015
he's a cancer specialist.

92
00:04:49,650 --> 00:04:51,198
That's where I saw you.

93
00:04:51,316 --> 00:04:54,292
If anyone has strong painkillers
and sedatives in his case,

94
00:04:54,410 --> 00:04:55,601
it's Judge Wargrave.

95
00:04:58,034 --> 00:04:59,505
Is that true, Judge?

96
00:05:00,453 --> 00:05:03,547
I have had health problems, yes.

97
00:05:03,666 --> 00:05:05,214
Then that's very cruel, Doctor.

98
00:05:05,331 --> 00:05:07,323
Don't blame me.
You pushed it.

99
00:05:07,434 --> 00:05:09,358
General, shall we?

100
00:05:18,682 --> 00:05:21,144
Just mild sedatives.

101
00:05:21,118 --> 00:05:22,284
As I said.

102
00:05:23,454 --> 00:05:24,564
Bog-standard.

103
00:05:25,128 --> 00:05:26,161
Nothing special.

104
00:05:26,077 --> 00:05:28,439
My surgery was a success.

105
00:05:29,249 --> 00:05:34,887
This... the house, the island...
Is meant to be my recuperation.

106
00:05:35,201 --> 00:05:40,287
Sea air, peace... and rest.

107
00:05:41,699 --> 00:05:44,204
Very sorry.
I'm... very sorry.

108
00:05:46,464 --> 00:05:47,654
Well, there's an end to it.

109
00:05:47,178 --> 00:05:48,344
Like hell it is.

110
00:05:49,662 --> 00:05:51,177
Why shouldn't she be searched?

111
00:05:52,810 --> 00:05:54,057
Equal rights for women.

112
00:05:55,484 --> 00:05:56,951
Let's see what you've got.

113
00:05:57,210 --> 00:06:01,153
Dr. Armstrong,
control yourself, please.

114
00:06:06,551 --> 00:06:08,392
Who the hell
do you think you are?

115
00:06:09,396 --> 00:06:12,343
I'm a doctor.
You're a secretary.

116
00:06:18,651 --> 00:06:20,042
Somebody moved them.

117
00:06:21,860 --> 00:06:22,794
They did.

118
00:06:23,427 --> 00:06:24,627
Someone did that.

119
00:06:51,153 --> 00:06:53,282
Did you really kill
all those men?

120
00:06:55,953 --> 00:06:59,385
Yes, Miss Claythorne.
I did kill all those men.

121
00:07:00,355 --> 00:07:01,546
And more.

122
00:07:02,576 --> 00:07:03,623
Why?

123
00:07:04,342 --> 00:07:06,899
It seemed like a good idea
at the time.

124
00:07:08,428 --> 00:07:09,824
They had something I wanted.

125
00:07:09,934 --> 00:07:11,915
In this case, it was diamonds.

126
00:07:13,148 --> 00:07:14,790
Worth more than a few lives.

127
00:07:16,162 --> 00:07:17,366
What about you?

128
00:07:21,993 --> 00:07:23,346
What did you want?

129
00:07:25,563 --> 00:07:27,548
I nearly drowned.

130
00:07:28,538 --> 00:07:31,394
I failed to save a little boy
in my care.

131
00:07:31,512 --> 00:07:33,146
And there isn't one minute
of every day

132
00:07:33,257 --> 00:07:35,249
that I am not sorry for that.

133
00:07:36,670 --> 00:07:37,817
Why aren't you?

134
00:07:38,136 --> 00:07:39,640
I know what I am.

135
00:07:41,072 --> 00:07:43,529
I always knew
it would catch up with me.

136
00:07:45,951 --> 00:07:47,055
And here it is.

137
00:08:48,527 --> 00:08:51,026
I love you,
I love you, I love you.

138
00:08:51,145 --> 00:08:53,212
I think about you
and you kissing me

139
00:08:53,327 --> 00:08:55,794
and your hands on me and in me
and your mouth on my body,

140
00:08:55,905 --> 00:08:58,737
and I cannot bear
that you are not with me now.

141
00:08:59,255 --> 00:09:03,445
I wish, I long,
I crave for you, my darling,

142
00:09:03,560 --> 00:09:07,169
and I feel so cruel
to poor, dear John,

143
00:09:07,883 --> 00:09:10,587
but the sun rises and sets
in your eyes, Henry.

144
00:09:11,334 --> 00:09:14,348
I love you.
I love you.

145
00:09:15,063 --> 00:09:16,773
"I am yours."

146
00:09:17,244 --> 00:09:19,306
The men are all ready
for the whistle, sir.

147
00:09:20,020 --> 00:09:21,906
Morale fairly good.

148
00:09:31,405 --> 00:09:33,666
Here.
Let me.

149
00:09:39,218 --> 00:09:40,495
Henry.

150
00:09:45,002 --> 00:09:51,354
You've been a...
a great friend to my wife and I.

151
00:09:57,178 --> 00:09:59,107
Perhaps you could call me John.

152
00:10:04,706 --> 00:10:07,173
Thank you, John.

153
00:10:22,702 --> 00:10:24,812
Myself and Mrs. Rogers were here
for a week

154
00:10:24,922 --> 00:10:26,232
without seeing another soul

155
00:10:26,351 --> 00:10:28,569
apart from Narracott
with the delivery, sir.

156
00:10:33,979 --> 00:10:34,931
Lombard.

157
00:10:36,318 --> 00:10:37,628
Where are you going?

158
00:10:37,746 --> 00:10:41,165
We're sat around
waiting for Ulick Norman Owen.

159
00:10:41,277 --> 00:10:43,268
What if he's been here
all along?

160
00:10:45,243 --> 00:10:47,224
Plenty of places
he could be hiding.

161
00:10:48,693 --> 00:10:49,803
Wait for me.

162
00:11:21,902 --> 00:11:26,035
Please, please,
please just fucking stop.

163
00:11:26,147 --> 00:11:29,923
Stop.
S-Stop. Stop. Stop.

164
00:11:45,503 --> 00:11:48,955
Oh, this is... this is barmy!

165
00:11:50,461 --> 00:11:52,246
No one could hide down there.

166
00:12:00,972 --> 00:12:04,186
Ever get the feeling
you're being hunted, Tubs?

167
00:12:04,304 --> 00:12:06,771
Now, stop calling me that.
I ain't even fat.

168
00:12:07,318 --> 00:12:09,028
And no, I don't.

169
00:12:09,143 --> 00:12:10,239
Really?

170
00:12:11,681 --> 00:12:16,781
'Cause Mr. Owen, whoever he may
be, knows a lot about us.

171
00:12:16,799 --> 00:12:18,909
Well, not about me.

172
00:12:19,019 --> 00:12:21,995
Edward Lander was a degenerate.
He was a pansy.

173
00:12:22,114 --> 00:12:25,013
He fell down the steps
into his cell.

174
00:12:34,313 --> 00:12:35,784
You never touched him?

175
00:12:37,644 --> 00:12:40,420
I wouldn't want to be near
one of them dirty bastards.

176
00:12:43,435 --> 00:12:45,339
Come on, Tubs!
Keep up!

177
00:12:58,649 --> 00:12:59,564
General?

178
00:13:00,375 --> 00:13:01,667
Is your suitcase ready?

179
00:13:04,776 --> 00:13:06,529
She died.

180
00:13:07,941 --> 00:13:11,074
Spanish influenza,
after the war.

181
00:13:11,717 --> 00:13:12,713
Who?

182
00:13:14,680 --> 00:13:16,146
My wife, Leslie.

183
00:13:16,913 --> 00:13:21,641
After all that...
she died of the Spanish flu.

184
00:13:26,772 --> 00:13:28,044
So many did.

185
00:13:28,756 --> 00:13:32,102
I should have just stepped aside
like a gentleman and...

186
00:13:32,620 --> 00:13:34,882
just let them be happy.

187
00:13:37,745 --> 00:13:40,688
Do come back to the house,
General.

188
00:13:41,156 --> 00:13:42,671
You haven't
brought your case down yet,

189
00:13:42,783 --> 00:13:46,059
and we want to get away as soon
as Mr. Narracott arrives.

190
00:13:48,574 --> 00:13:51,160
He's not coming, Narracott,
you know.

191
00:13:51,271 --> 00:13:53,575
No one's coming for us.

192
00:13:54,047 --> 00:13:55,638
We won't be leaving the island.

193
00:13:55,753 --> 00:13:56,987
This is the end.

194
00:13:59,879 --> 00:14:03,687
It's a relief to come to
the end, to know that it's over.

195
00:14:04,241 --> 00:14:07,098
You won't understand that yet,
but you will...

196
00:14:07,216 --> 00:14:08,702
In time.

197
00:14:11,226 --> 00:14:13,049
I think you're quite mistaken.

198
00:14:14,038 --> 00:14:16,938
The boat will come and we'll all
be waiting for you.

199
00:15:12,016 --> 00:15:13,887
Miss Claythorne.

200
00:15:14,436 --> 00:15:15,388
Good.

201
00:15:15,982 --> 00:15:18,212
Bring a couple of chairs,
would you?

202
00:15:27,168 --> 00:15:28,302
What's going on?

203
00:15:28,913 --> 00:15:30,980
It's a bit early
to be on the sauce.

204
00:15:31,809 --> 00:15:33,280
It's been something
of a morning.

205
00:15:33,395 --> 00:15:34,671
Hey. Hey.

206
00:15:39,545 --> 00:15:42,320
Bastard's down there.
I heard him.

207
00:15:42,439 --> 00:15:43,510
What bastard?

208
00:15:44,874 --> 00:15:46,031
Owen.

209
00:15:46,143 --> 00:15:48,448
I can hear him moving about.

210
00:15:48,999 --> 00:15:50,270
Marston's room.

211
00:16:15,298 --> 00:16:16,551
What are you doing?

212
00:16:23,502 --> 00:16:24,973
Camp bed.

213
00:16:25,088 --> 00:16:27,588
Well, we had to find somewhere
to store it, and...

214
00:16:28,103 --> 00:16:30,050
young men don't look under beds.

215
00:16:30,165 --> 00:16:31,994
But w-what do you need
a camp bed for?

216
00:16:32,108 --> 00:16:33,179
What were you planning?

217
00:16:33,299 --> 00:16:35,484
Well, I can't sleep in my room,
can I?

218
00:16:35,599 --> 00:16:36,595
Me wife.

219
00:16:36,710 --> 00:16:38,939
Yeah. Obviously.
Of course.

220
00:16:39,566 --> 00:16:41,590
I've got to find somewhere else
to set up.

221
00:16:41,708 --> 00:16:43,255
What for?
We're all leaving.

222
00:16:43,374 --> 00:16:46,198
Well, you might be.
This is my job.

223
00:16:46,309 --> 00:16:48,733
I can't go anywhere
until my employer dismisses me.

224
00:16:48,847 --> 00:16:51,314
Your employer?
Your employer is insane.

225
00:16:51,425 --> 00:16:55,558
Be that as it may,
I've got nothing else to go to.

226
00:16:56,740 --> 00:16:58,969
All right, then.
Carry on, Rogers.

227
00:17:04,879 --> 00:17:06,578
Did you know he had a gun?

228
00:17:07,496 --> 00:17:08,625
No.

229
00:17:22,609 --> 00:17:24,394
Do stop.

230
00:17:24,513 --> 00:17:26,655
Mr. Narracott seems
a sensible man.

231
00:17:26,774 --> 00:17:28,202
He'll be here.

232
00:17:31,295 --> 00:17:34,033
I must say, I understand now

233
00:17:34,151 --> 00:17:37,722
why you teach in such
a substandard establishment.

234
00:17:39,546 --> 00:17:42,089
I'm just observing
that most schools

235
00:17:42,203 --> 00:17:44,627
would not want to be associated
with an inquest.

236
00:17:44,742 --> 00:17:45,900
I'm not accusing you.

237
00:17:46,011 --> 00:17:47,915
There's been quite enough
of that already.

238
00:17:48,034 --> 00:17:49,343
Yes, there has.

239
00:17:49,462 --> 00:17:50,814
More than enough.

240
00:17:50,929 --> 00:17:53,040
Apart from the egregious
Mr. Lombard

241
00:17:53,151 --> 00:17:55,694
and the Rogers,
who I find most dubious,

242
00:17:55,808 --> 00:18:00,655
and the depraved Mr. Marston,
it's all nonsense.

243
00:18:00,766 --> 00:18:03,591
Everyone was simply doing
their duty.

244
00:18:04,507 --> 00:18:05,903
As was I.

245
00:18:07,164 --> 00:18:08,235
As were you?

246
00:18:08,354 --> 00:18:10,573
You didn't say anything
last night.

247
00:18:11,646 --> 00:18:13,588
It wasn't for gentlemen's ears.

248
00:18:13,907 --> 00:18:17,002
But Beatrice Taylor was my
maid of all work.

249
00:18:18,310 --> 00:18:20,095
Foundling girl.

250
00:18:20,213 --> 00:18:24,974
An unwanted...
From the war, you know?

251
00:18:27,551 --> 00:18:31,241
I believed her to be a clean,
decent, modest girl.

252
00:18:31,559 --> 00:18:33,702
I taught her needlework skills.

253
00:18:33,821 --> 00:18:35,768
We had quite the little home.

254
00:19:00,242 --> 00:19:02,271
But then she got herself
into trouble.

255
00:19:03,257 --> 00:19:04,548
The family way.

256
00:19:06,469 --> 00:19:10,541
As her own loose mother had
with her.

257
00:19:11,309 --> 00:19:13,238
She begged me for help.

258
00:19:14,085 --> 00:19:16,947
Naturally and quite properly,
I refused.

259
00:19:23,129 --> 00:19:25,477
Miss Brent, please!

260
00:19:29,792 --> 00:19:31,502
I beg you!

261
00:19:33,600 --> 00:19:35,071
What happened to her?

262
00:19:35,186 --> 00:19:36,820
She threw herself under a train.

263
00:19:36,932 --> 00:19:38,479
She killed herself?

